Let \( x_{1}, x_{2}, \cdots, x_{n} \) and \( a_{1}, a_{2}, \cdots, a_{n} \) be sequences of arbitrary real numbers satisfying the following conditions:
1. \( x_{1}+x_{2}+\cdots+x_{n}=0 \);
2. \( \left|x_{1}\right|+\left|x_{2}\right|+\cdots+\left|x_{n}\right|=1 \);
3. \( a_{1} \geqslant a_{2} \geqslant \cdots \geqslant a_{n} \).

Find the minimum value of \( A \) such that the inequality \( \mid a_{1} x_{1}+a_{2} x_{2}+\cdots+a_{n} x_{n} \mid \leqslant A\left(a_{1}-a_{n}\right) \) holds.

